From adbf2cebde437f417952781eb033c6308fa26f9f Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Keno Fischer <keno@juliahub.com>
Date: Fri, 17 Jul 2026 22:38:42 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 1/8] futex: Replay the wakeup consumed by a robust waiter
 killed before acquiring

A robust futex unlock stores 0 over the whole futex value - wiping
FUTEX_WAITERS - and wakes a single waiter. That wakeup is a one-shot
notification: the protocol relies on its recipient to either acquire
the futex (and eventually unlock while aware of the remaining
contention) or re-arm FUTEX_WAITERS before sleeping again.

If the woken waiter is killed before it can do either, and a third
task re-acquired the futex through the uncontended fast path in the
meantime, the notification is lost: the exit time robust list walk
finds the waiter's armed list_op_pending, reads a futex value owned by
a live task and - correctly - leaves the futex value alone, but it
also discards the wakeup. The new owner sees no FUTEX_WAITERS when it
unlocks and wakes nobody. The remaining waiters sleep forever behind a
free futex:

  A owns the futex, B and C sleep in FUTEX_WAIT
                                        uval == A | FUTEX_WAITERS
  A robust unlock: store 0, FUTEX_WAKE(1) wakes B
                                        uval == 0
  D fast path acquire: cmpxchg(0 -> D)
                                        uval == D, no FUTEX_WAITERS
  B killed before acting on the wakeup
  B exit walk, pending op: owner D != B -> no action
  D unlock: no FUTEX_WAITERS -> no wake
                                        C sleeps forever

Commit ca16d5bee598 ("futex: Prevent robust futex exit race") set out
to handle exactly this scenario - its comment spells out "a woken up
waiter is killed before it can acquire the futex in user space" - but
only covers it while the futex value is still 0 when the exit walk
runs. If the futex was re-acquired first, the owner mismatch check
discards the pending op, and the consumed wakeup with it. Both are the
same situation - a pending lock operation on a futex the dying task
does not own, whose wakeup may have been consumed - so fold the owner
mismatch case into that special case: wake one waiter whenever a
pending non PI lock operation is discarded because the owner part of
the futex value does not match the dying task, unless the value
carries a live owner together with FUTEX_WAITERS. The futex value is
not touched either way, and a spurious wakeup is harmless: woken
waiters re-evaluate the futex value and re-arm FUTEX_WAITERS before
sleeping again, which also repairs the wiped bit for the remaining
sleepers.

If FUTEX_WAITERS is set again by the time the walk runs, no wakeup
needs to be replayed: within the protocol the bit is only ever cleared
by an unlock which issues a wakeup (lock attempts and the exit walk
itself preserve it), so an observed FUTEX_WAITERS guarantees a future
wakeup from the live owner's unlock and the chain is already intact.
This also holds when the task which re-armed the bit dies before
sleeping - the bit stays behind either way. This meaning of the bit is
part of the non PI robust futex ABI, not merely libc convention: the
exit walk itself preserves FUTEX_WAITERS when it marks a dead owner's
futex (mval) and issues its own wakeup only when the bit is set, so
the kernel already requires unlock paths to honor an armed bit.

The window was found by model checking the robust futex wait/wake
interactions with TLC. A deterministic selftest is added in the
following patch.

This patch was developed with the assistance of Claude (an AI
assistant by Anthropic); the author reviewed, validated and takes
responsibility for the changes.

Fixes: ca16d5bee598 ("futex: Prevent robust futex exit race")
Signed-off-by: Keno Fischer <keno@juliahub.com>
---
 kernel/futex/core.c | 67 +++++++++++++++++++++++++--------------------
 1 file changed, 37 insertions(+), 30 deletions(-)

diff --git a/kernel/futex/core.c b/kernel/futex/core.c
index 179b26e9c934..add8ade29e47 100644
--- a/kernel/futex/core.c
+++ b/kernel/futex/core.c
@@ -982,8 +982,10 @@ static int handle_futex_death(u32 __user *uaddr, struct task_struct *curr,
 		return -1;
 
 	/*
-	 * Special case for regular (non PI) futexes. The unlock path in
-	 * user space has two race scenarios:
+	 * Special case for regular (non PI) futexes: the dying task holds
+	 * a pending lock operation (@pending_op == true) on a futex whose
+	 * owner part does not match its TID. The unlock path in user
+	 * space has two race scenarios leading here:
 	 *
 	 * 1. The unlock path releases the user space futex value and
 	 *    before it can execute the futex() syscall to wake up
@@ -992,42 +994,47 @@ static int handle_futex_death(u32 __user *uaddr, struct task_struct *curr,
 	 * 2. A woken up waiter is killed before it can acquire the
 	 *    futex in user space.
 	 *
-	 * In the second case, the wake up notification could be generated
-	 * by the unlock path in user space after setting the futex value
-	 * to zero or by the kernel after setting the OWNER_DIED bit below.
+	 * In the first case the futex value is 0. In the second case it
+	 * may be 0, carry OWNER_DIED (set by this walk running for an
+	 * earlier death), or carry the TID of a third task which
+	 * re-acquired the futex through the uncontended fast path after
+	 * the robust unlock - which stored 0 over the whole futex value,
+	 * wiping FUTEX_WAITERS - woke the now dying waiter.
 	 *
-	 * In both cases the TID validation below prevents a wakeup of
-	 * potential waiters which can cause these waiters to block
-	 * forever.
+	 * The futex value must not be touched: a zero value is a
+	 * consistent unlocked state which a woken waiter just takes over
+	 * (setting the OWNER_DIED bit would create inconsistent state
+	 * and malfunction of the user space owner died handling), an
+	 * OWNER_DIED value is already being dealt with by its waiters,
+	 * and a foreign TID is a lock with a live owner.
 	 *
-	 * In both cases the following conditions are met:
-	 *
-	 *	1) task->futex.robust_list->list_op_pending != NULL
-	 *	   @pending_op == true
-	 *	2) The owner part of user space futex value == 0
-	 *	3) Regular futex: @pi == false
-	 *
-	 * If these conditions are met, it is safe to attempt waking up a
-	 * potential waiter without touching the user space futex value and
-	 * trying to set the OWNER_DIED bit. If the futex value is zero,
-	 * the rest of the user space mutex state is consistent, so a woken
-	 * waiter will just take over the uncontended futex. Setting the
-	 * OWNER_DIED bit would create inconsistent state and malfunction
-	 * of the user space owner died handling. Otherwise, the OWNER_DIED
-	 * bit is already set, and the woken waiter is expected to deal with
-	 * this.
+	 * But without the TID validation below suppressing them, this
+	 * walk would have generated a wake up - and the dying task may
+	 * have consumed exactly one wake up which nobody else will
+	 * re-issue: the notification of the robust unlock in scenario 2.
+	 * Replay it, or the remaining waiters block forever behind an
+	 * owner which will never see contention; a spurious wake up is
+	 * harmless, as woken waiters re-evaluate the futex value and
+	 * re-arm FUTEX_WAITERS before sleeping again. The replay is not
+	 * needed while the futex value carries a live owner and
+	 * FUTEX_WAITERS: the bit is only ever cleared by an unlock which
+	 * issues a wake up (lock attempts and this walk preserve it), so
+	 * an observed FUTEX_WAITERS guarantees a future wake up from the
+	 * owner's unlock and no wake up was consumed. For a released
+	 * futex value the wake up is unconditional - the unlock which
+	 * released it wiped the bit, and there is no owner whose future
+	 * unlock could deliver a wake up.
 	 */
 	owner = uval & FUTEX_TID_MASK;
 
-	if (pending_op && !pi && !owner) {
-		futex_wake(uaddr, FLAGS_SIZE_32 | FLAGS_SHARED, NULL, 1,
-			   FUTEX_BITSET_MATCH_ANY);
+	if (owner != task_pid_vnr(curr)) {
+		if (pending_op && !pi &&
+		    (!owner || !(uval & FUTEX_WAITERS)))
+			futex_wake(uaddr, FLAGS_SIZE_32 | FLAGS_SHARED, NULL, 1,
+				   FUTEX_BITSET_MATCH_ANY);
 		return 0;
 	}
 
-	if (owner != task_pid_vnr(curr))
-		return 0;
-
 	/*
 	 * Ok, this dying thread is truly holding a futex
 	 * of interest. Set the OWNER_DIED bit atomically
-- 
